  "method": [
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Start by prepping the pork the night before or at least 3 hrs prior. Begin by puncturing the entire pork skin with a knife, then generously sprinkle sea salt all over the skin. Next, score the flesh side of the pork both vertically and horizontally."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Blend all the jerk paste ingredients together. Reserve one-third of the jerk paste and massage the remaining two-thirds into the pork flesh only."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Place the prepared pork on a rack-lined tray in the fridge. Leave uncovered overnight to allow the flavours to soak in and the skin to dry."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "On the day of cooking, heat the oven to 160°C. Remove the pork from the fridge and wipe away any excess salt from the skin, ensuring it's thoroughly dry."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Roast the pork in a roasting tin for approximately 40 mins until tender."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "While the pork is cooking, thinly slice the carrot, shallot, peppers, Scotch bonnet and mango into julienne strips. Set aside."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Prepare the pickling liquor by combining the apple cider vinegar, sugar, white peppercorns and pimento seeds in a small saucepan. Add water, to taste. Simmer over a low heat for 5 mins until the sugar completely dissolves."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Place all the julienned vegetables (except the mango) into a heatproof bowl and pour the pickling liquor over them. Wrap the bowl in cling film to enhance the flavours."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Pick the coriander leaves and set them aside in cold water to keep them fresh."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "After the initial 40 mins of cooking, increase the oven temperature to 220°C and continue to roast the pork for an additional 20-25 mins until the skin starts to blister and turns golden brown. Turn the grill onto low, then transfer the bellies under until the skin goes crispy and crackles, 3-6 mins.Let the pork rest for 15-20 mins before chopping."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Meanwhile, combine the reserved jerk paste with 2 tbsp water and 2 tbsp honey in a saucepan. Heat over a medium heat until it thickens into a sticky glaze."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Slice the pork bellies and brush with the prepared honey jerk glaze."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Cut open the baguettes and spread mayonnaise over the bread."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Layer slices of the glazed pork onto the bread, then top with the pickled vegetables and fresh coriander."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Serve and enjoy your flavourful crispy honey jerk pork bánh mì."
    }
  ],
